Those are the last 40 or so Best Picture winners! What will win this year? Smart money is on "Who Gives a Fuck?" and "Seriously, Who Cares?"
2013: 12 Years A Slave: Won despite having the same basic plot as "Dumb & Dumber."
2012: Argo: Somehow overcame huge odds to win despite, you know, Ben Affleck.
2011: The Artist: Today, most people just call this movie "Prince" instead.
2010: The King's Speech: Historical inaccuracy: In real life, the king recited Samuel L. Jackson's speech from "Pulp Fiction."
2009: The Hurt Locker: One of over 1,200 films that year based on the novel "Push" by Sapphire.
2008: Slumdog Millionaire: Has the most intense torture scenes of any game show-oriented film since "Match Game '76: The Movie."
2007: No Country For Old Men: The Coen Brothers' surprising take on "Logan's Run."
2006: The Departed: On his Oscar, Martin Scorsese crossed out "The Departed" and wrote in "Raging Bull, Taxi Driver & King Of Comedy."
2005: Crash: The only movie that year to NOT feature two star-crossed cowboys in love.
2004: Million Dollar Baby: Due to the current economic situation, this movie has been re-titled "$112 Baby."
2003: The Return Of The King: This Elvis biopic takes a LOT of liberties, though Gollum is pretty much dead on.
2002: Chicago: The biopic of the band that did the cheesy '70s ballad "If You Leave Me Now."
2001: A Beautiful Mind: When we think of beautiful minds, Russell Crowe is WAY down the list, somewhere between Dick Cheney and Gallagher.
2000: Gladiator: Even the "Do you like movies about gladiators?" guy in Airplane! hated this movie.
1999: American Beauty: SPOILER: The plastic bag turns out to be Keyser Soze.
1998: Shakespeare In Love: Sadly, the sequel "Shakespeare In Ugly, Protracted Divorce Proceedings" flopped.
1997: Titanic: If Leonardo DiCaprio is king of the world, can we PLEASE have a revolution? Jesus.
1996: The English Patient: The story of a man with terminal case of British teeth.
1995: Braveheart: Looking back, here's where we should have realized Mel Gibson was kinda nuts.
1994: Forrest Gump: The entire movie was shot on shrimp film stock, with shrimp lights on shrimp film sets.
1993: Schindler's List: That was one intense grocery list. Theaters refused to seat people during the Choosing A Ripe Cantaloupe scene.
1992: Unforgiven: One of only five Metallica songs to win Best Picture.
1991: The Silence Of The Lambs: Sales of baskets and lotion skyrocketed.
1990: Dances With Wolves: The sequel "Air Guitar With Badgers" was a dismal failure.
@MatthewSoffer We tweeted C of F.
1989: Driving Miss Daisy: NASCAR fans were profoundly disappointed that only one flaming tire flew into the audience the entire movie.
1988: Rain Man: Kind of a sucky superpower, when you think about it.
